//! Adversarial divergence audit of `ferrolearn_linear::LassoLars`
//! (`method="lasso"`) against the live scikit-learn 1.5.2 oracle, plus a
//! passing `ferrolearn_linear::Lars` (`method="lar"`) regression control.
//!
//! Mirrors `sklearn.linear_model.LassoLars` / `Lars`
//! (`sklearn/linear_model/_least_angle.py`). The Lasso path is the equiangular
//! LARS-Lasso homotopy with the Efron section 3.3 DROP condition: when an active
//! coefficient is about to cross zero on the current equiangular step, the step
//! is truncated and that feature is dropped from the active set before the
//! direction is recomputed (`_lars_path_solver`, `method == "lasso"` branch,
//! `sklearn/linear_model/_least_angle.py:413+`, the sign-change / `drop_idx`
//! handling around `:680-740`).
//!
//! ferrolearn's `LassoLars::fit` instead runs forward-stepwise OLS
//! (`fn ols_active in lars.rs`) with a sign-flip drop heuristic and never routes
//! through the `lasso_modification` branch of `fn lars_path`. On the diabetes
//! dataset this yields a DIFFERENT active set and DIFFERENT coefficients than
//! sklearn (REQ-2 / AC-2, blocker #482).
//!
//! All expected values are computed by live-calling sklearn 1.5.2 (R-CHAR-3):
//! ```text
//! from sklearn.linear_model import LassoLars, Lars
//! from sklearn.datasets import load_diabetes
//! X, y = load_diabetes(return_X_y=True)
//! LassoLars(alpha=0.1).fit(X, y).coef_   # SK_LASSO_A01
//! LassoLars(alpha=0.5).fit(X, y).coef_   # SK_LASSO_A05
//! Lars(n_nonzero_coefs=5).fit(X, y).coef_  # SK_LARS_5 (control, PASSES)
//! ```

